      "subsections": [
        {
          "id": "B.I.1",
          "title": "Executive summary",
          "heading_level": 3,
          "blocks": [
            {
              "type": "callout",
              "tone": "verdict",
              "iaja": "J",
              "text": "Demand-Driven EPSU looks the cleaner of the two setups present — the supply side is ambiguous and may be a trap. Keep probing at ESA; do not promote to DD without independent corroboration of the price-path assumption."
            },
            {
              "type": "prose",
              "iaja": "A",
              "text": "Lorem ipsum structure of the argument runs: (a) real-world LNG balance tightens through 2027 as EU import cover falls; (b) Novatek captures incremental pricing given cost-curve position; (c) market still discounts at mid-cycle multiples. Three layers, each with its own evidence stack; the deepest doubt sits on (c)."
            },
            {
              "type": "bullet_group",
              "items": [
                {
                  "iaja": "J",
                  "text": "PRIMARY driver: LNG price path N1-3Y. Everything else is second order.",
                  "sub": [
                    {
                      "iaja": "I",
                      "text": "Spot TTF forward curve still backwardated from winter peak."
                    },
                    {
                      "iaja": "I",
                      "text": "EU storage at 74% of capacity into refill season, above 5y avg."
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "iaja": "J",
                  "text": "SECONDARY driver: upstream capex cycle — late-cycle exuberance could compress the window.",
                  "sub": [
                    {
                      "iaja": "A",
                      "text": "Rig count proxy at +18% y/y — consistent with supply catch-up beginning."
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "iaja": "J",
                  "text": "TERTIARY driver: RUB/USD — mostly noise for this thesis; include for completeness."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "prose",
              "iaja": "A",
              "ratings": [
                {
                  "grade": "A",
                  "attr": "setup quality"
                }
              ],
              "text": "Excepteur sint occaecat cupidatat non proident, sunt in culpa qui officia deserunt mollit anim id est laborum. The strength of the setup is in the asymmetry: if the PRIMARY driver resolves as expected, multiple expansion compounds EPS growth; if it disappoints, downside is cushioned by the net cash position and shareholder yield."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
